		<div class="comment_text"><p>I've been (and my company) a Dell customer for decades... and while I trust them with my business laptop and my servers, I've been building my own desktops for years. With a little bit of research, I can get the same features at a cheaper price but, better still, I can exceed what the vendor would give me and install the best component for my needs.</p><p>I've fallen in love with the new case from Antec (the Skeleton). Quiet, easy access and a work of art. Get all the ram, disk, video, sound power you desire. Start with deciding what cpu/graphics combo you want to go with and research the best bang for your buck (<a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnewegg.com%3ACj9TjZIeIczQtT1sdGCwmTuN68A&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="newegg.com">newegg.com</a> is a great resource as is MaximumPC magazine). Then you add in your drives, sound (if not using mb based) and you get the fun of building it... with practice you can build out in two hours.</p><p>My latest build would have cost $2500 on <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fdell.com%3AwGjNTnQog5D-Dss0VCTc1TtpbuM&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="dell.com">dell.com</a> but mine cost $1450 with more disk and better case/video. Try it and have fun!</p></div>
